  "text": "Conventional SISO methods are applied using the developed linear coupled model. Therefore, the open and closed loop polezero map is plotted for various proportional and integral gains. The range of the proportional gains k p is selected such that the movement of the poles from the open loop pole towards the open loop zero is visible and also some platform poles with a positive real part result. As in [CITATION_1] the underlying idea is that increasing proportional gains generally improve the performance of the rotor speed tracking, while they can lead to instability of the floating platform. Thus, a well suited controller can be designed by selecting stable closed loop platform poles, close to the imaginary axis, with their corresponding gains k p and T i . This method for baseline controller design of FOWT assumes that with the described pole placement the compromise between rotor speed tracking and stable platform motion is close to the optimum. Subsequently, a nonlinear simulation model with realistic disturbances is used to find the optimal combination of proportional gain and integral gain time constant T i .",
